The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Thursday, June 10, 2004  The City Diary
																																																																																		Two city businessmen, Harsh Mutsuddi, 30, and Rajesh Gupta, 39, suffered serious injuries on Monday evening when they were beaten up by Basudeb Patra alias Basu and other members of a club near Kashi Mitra Ghat Street. The businessmen had paid less than what the club members had demanded of them as Sitala puja subscription. The injured had to be hospitalised.																																																								Basu, was arrested later on charges of extortion and attempt to murder. Produced in court on Tuesday, he has been remanded to police custody till June 15, said Dulal Chandra Dey, officer-in-charge of Shyampukur police station. 																																																								n Monday, Basu and an accomplice had demanded Rs 500 from Mutsuddi and Gupta ,who managed to cough up Rs 300. Basu left to return later with three others. Armed with sticks and rods, they beat up Gupta and Mutsuddi, who had to be taken to R.G. Kar Medical College and Hospital. Gupta lost a few teeth while Mutsuddi, in a critical condition, was transferred to Calcutta Medical College and Hospital, and later to a private nursing home.																																																		The US Consulate and the American Center as well as the US Embassy will remain closed on Friday, following an announcement by American President George W. Bush, proclaiming June 11 as a National Day of Mourning for Ronald Reagan. 																																																		Police on Wednesday recovered jewellery and cash worth nearly Rs 3 lakhs, stolen recently from an apartment in BF block of Salt Lake. M. Saha, additional superintendent of police, Bidhannagar, said the lone domestic help of the residence, Bholanath Maity was traced to a relatives house in Labony where he was caught red-handed with the booty.																																																		Three persons were arrested and one managed to escape after robbing Rs 1,200 from a taxi driver and injuring him with a razor on Tuesday night. According to Lake police station officials, a group of five had boarded the taxi on Rashbehari Avenue.																																																		A 72-year-old woman, Janaki Devi, was injured, when she was hit by a private bus on route 107 on Wednesday morning on ATM Road in Bhowanipore. Janaki Devi was rushed to SSKM Hospital, from where she was released later. Police have impounded the vehicle and arrested the driver.																																																		Traffic flow was affected for several hours in the Calcutta flank of VIP Road when a loaded truck overturned at Joramandir crossing on Wednesday morning. 																																																		Ambassador of Israel in India, David Danieli called on mayor Subrata Mukherjee at the CMC headquarters on Wednesday. Danieli was accompanied by industrialist Harshavardhan Neotia. To Shradha Eye Care Centre and Lions Club of Calcutta for conducting free eye operations on 90 underprivileged persons at Alipore.
